      <h1>Pregnancy Week by Week: A Complete Trimester Guide</h1>
      <p class="article-intro">Pregnancy is a remarkable 40-week journey during which a single fertilized cell develops into a fully formed baby ready to enter the world. Each week brings new developmental milestones, physical changes, and questions about what is normal, what to expect next, and how to take the best care of yourself and your growing baby. This comprehensive guide walks you through all three trimesters, explaining key developments week by week, describing common symptoms and how to manage them, providing a prenatal care checklist, and offering evidence-based nutrition guidance. Use our <a href="/due-date/">due date calculator</a> to estimate when your baby will arrive based on your last menstrual period or conception date.</p>
    </header>

    <section>
      <h2>How Pregnancy Weeks Are Counted</h2>
      <p>Before diving into the week-by-week guide, it is important to understand how pregnancy is dated. Pregnancy weeks are counted from the first day of your last menstrual period (LMP), not from the date of conception. This means that during weeks one and two of "pregnancy," you have not yet conceived. Ovulation and fertilization typically occur around week two, and implantation of the fertilized egg in the uterine wall happens around week three to four.</p>
      <p>This dating convention exists because the LMP date is usually known with certainty, whereas the exact date of conception is often unknown. A full-term pregnancy is 40 weeks (280 days) from the LMP, although babies born anywhere from 37 to 42 weeks are considered within the normal range. Your healthcare provider may adjust your estimated due date based on first-trimester ultrasound measurements, which are the most accurate method for dating a pregnancy.</p>
      <p>Pregnancy is divided into three trimesters. The first trimester encompasses weeks one through twelve. The second trimester covers weeks thirteen through twenty-seven. The third trimester spans weeks twenty-eight through forty. Each trimester has distinct characteristics in terms of fetal development, maternal symptoms, and prenatal care milestones.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>First Trimester: Weeks 1 Through 12</h2>
      <p>The first trimester is a period of extraordinarily rapid development. By the end of week twelve, your baby will have gone from a single cell to a fully formed miniature human with all major organs and body systems in place. This is also the trimester when many women experience the most intense pregnancy symptoms, including nausea, fatigue, and breast tenderness.</p>

      <h3>Weeks 1-4: Conception and Implantation</h3>
      <p>During weeks one and two, your body is preparing for ovulation. Around week two, an egg is released from the ovary and, if sperm is present, fertilization occurs in the fallopian tube. The fertilized egg, now called a zygote, begins dividing rapidly as it travels down the fallopian tube toward the uterus. By around day five, it has become a blastocyst, a hollow ball of about 100 cells. Between days six and twelve after fertilization (around week three to four of pregnancy), the blastocyst implants in the uterine wall, a process that may cause light spotting known as implantation bleeding. By week four, the embryo is about the size of a poppy seed, and a home pregnancy test may begin to show a positive result as the hormone hCG rises.</p>

      <h3>Weeks 5-8: Organ Formation Begins</h3>
      <p>Week five marks the beginning of the embryonic period, when major organ systems start to form. The neural tube, which becomes the brain and spinal cord, closes during weeks five to six, which is why adequate folic acid intake before and during early pregnancy is so critical. The heart begins beating at around week five to six, and by week six, tiny limb buds that will become arms and legs are visible. By week eight, the embryo is about the size of a raspberry, all major organs have begun to form, facial features including eyes, ears, and nostrils are taking shape, and fingers and toes are starting to develop. This period is when the embryo is most vulnerable to the effects of harmful substances, making it essential to avoid alcohol, tobacco, recreational drugs, and unnecessary medications.</p>

      <h3>Weeks 9-12: Fetal Period Begins</h3>
      <p>At week nine, the embryo officially becomes a fetus. Bones begin to harden, and the reproductive organs start developing, although it is too early to determine sex by ultrasound. By week ten, all vital organs are formed and beginning to function, and the fetus is about the size of a prune. Fingernails and toenails start growing. By week twelve, the fetus is about the size of a lime (approximately 2.5 inches long), reflexes are developing, and the kidneys begin producing urine. The risk of miscarriage drops significantly after the end of the first trimester, which is why many parents choose to share their pregnancy news at this point.</p>

      <h3>Common First Trimester Symptoms</h3>
      <p>Morning sickness (nausea and vomiting, which can occur at any time of day) affects approximately 70 to 80 percent of pregnant women, typically beginning around week six and peaking between weeks eight and twelve. Extreme fatigue is common due to rising progesterone levels and the enormous energy demands of early fetal development. Breast tenderness and swelling occur as the body prepares for future milk production. Frequent urination increases as the uterus grows and presses on the bladder, and as blood volume increases, causing the kidneys to process more fluid. Food aversions and heightened sense of smell are common and may contribute to nausea. Mood swings are driven by hormonal changes and the emotional adjustment to pregnancy.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Second Trimester: Weeks 13 Through 27</h2>
      <p>The second trimester is often called the "golden period" of pregnancy. For many women, the nausea and fatigue of the first trimester subside, energy returns, and the discomforts of the third trimester have not yet begun. This is also when pregnancy becomes visible as the abdomen grows, and when most women feel their baby move for the first time.</p>

      <h3>Weeks 13-16: Growth and Movement</h3>
      <p>At the beginning of the second trimester, the fetus is about 3 inches long and weighs about an ounce. Growth accelerates rapidly. By week fourteen, the fetus can make facial expressions such as squinting and frowning. Fine hair called lanugo covers the body to help regulate temperature. By week sixteen, the fetus is about 4.5 inches long and may begin to hear sounds. The skeletal system continues to harden from cartilage to bone. For women who have been pregnant before, fetal movement (quickening) may be felt as early as week sixteen, though first-time mothers typically do not feel it until weeks eighteen to twenty-five.</p>

      <h3>Weeks 17-20: Halfway Point</h3>
      <p>The anatomy scan ultrasound, one of the most anticipated prenatal appointments, typically occurs between weeks eighteen and twenty-two. This detailed ultrasound examines the baby's organs, bones, and overall development, and for many parents, it is when they learn the baby's sex. By week eighteen, the fetus is about the size of a bell pepper and weighs approximately 7 ounces. The nervous system is maturing rapidly, and the fetus develops a protective coating called vernix caseosa. By week twenty, you have reached the halfway point of pregnancy. The fetus is about 6.5 inches long, weighs about 10 ounces, and is increasingly active with kicks, rolls, and somersaults.</p>

      <h3>Weeks 21-27: Viability Milestone</h3>
      <p>During this period, the fetus gains weight steadily and the lungs continue maturing. By week twenty-two, eyebrows and eyelids are formed. By week twenty-three, the fetus reaches the threshold of viability, meaning that with intensive medical intervention, survival outside the womb becomes possible, though outcomes at this stage are still very uncertain. By week twenty-four, the lungs begin producing surfactant, a substance essential for breathing air. By week twenty-seven, the fetus weighs about two pounds, can open and close its eyes, has regular sleep-wake cycles, and may respond to light and sound. The brain is developing rapidly, with billions of neurons forming new connections.</p>

      <h3>Common Second Trimester Symptoms</h3>
      <p>As the uterus expands, round ligament pain (sharp or aching pain in the lower abdomen or groin) is common and harmless. Skin changes may include a dark line down the abdomen (linea nigra), darkening of the nipples and areolae, and patches of darker skin on the face (melasma or the mask of pregnancy). Nasal congestion and nosebleeds can occur due to increased blood flow. Back pain often begins as the growing belly shifts your center of gravity. Leg cramps, particularly at night, are common and may be related to changes in circulation and mineral balance. Braxton Hicks contractions, irregular practice contractions that feel like a tightening of the abdomen, may begin in the second trimester.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Third Trimester: Weeks 28 Through 40</h2>
      <p>The third trimester is a period of rapid fetal growth and final preparation for birth. The baby gains most of its birth weight during these weeks, and the lungs, brain, and other organs undergo critical final maturation. For the mother, this trimester often brings increasing physical discomfort as the baby takes up more space, along with growing anticipation and preparation for delivery.</p>

      <h3>Weeks 28-32: Rapid Growth</h3>
      <p>At week twenty-eight, the fetus weighs about 2.2 pounds and is approximately 14.8 inches long. The brain is developing rapidly, with the surface becoming increasingly wrinkled as new neural connections form. The bones are fully developed but still soft and pliable for delivery. By week thirty, the fetus weighs about 3 pounds, and the lanugo (fine body hair) begins to disappear. The fetus practices breathing movements by inhaling amniotic fluid. By week thirty-two, the fetus weighs about 3.75 pounds, the toenails are visible, and the baby has developed a fully functional immune system. Most babies born at this stage survive with medical support, though they benefit greatly from additional weeks of development.</p>

      <h3>Weeks 33-36: Preparing for Birth</h3>
      <p>During these weeks, the baby gains about half a pound per week. Fat accumulates under the skin, giving the baby a rounder, less wrinkled appearance and providing insulation for temperature regulation after birth. By week thirty-four, the lungs are nearly mature, and babies born at this stage generally do well with minimal medical intervention. By week thirty-six, the baby is about 18.5 inches long and weighs about 6 pounds. Many babies settle into a head-down position in preparation for birth during this period. The vernix caseosa coating begins to thin, and the baby may descend lower into the pelvis (called lightening or dropping), which can relieve shortness of breath but increase pelvic pressure and urinary frequency.</p>

      <h3>Weeks 37-40: Full Term</h3>
      <p>At week thirty-seven, the pregnancy is considered early term. The baby is fully developed and could be born safely at any time. The lungs and brain continue their final maturation. By week thirty-nine (full term), the baby typically weighs 7 to 8 pounds and is about 20 inches long. The baby is gaining about half an ounce of fat per day, which will help maintain body temperature after birth. By the due date at week forty, the placenta begins to age, and labor is likely to begin naturally. If labor does not start by week forty-one to forty-two, your healthcare provider will discuss induction options, as prolonged pregnancy carries increased risks.</p>

      <h3>Common Third Trimester Symptoms</h3>
      <p>Shortness of breath is common as the growing uterus pushes against the diaphragm. Heartburn and acid reflux intensify for the same reason. Swelling (edema) in the feet, ankles, and hands is normal due to increased fluid retention, though sudden or severe swelling should be reported to your healthcare provider as it can be a sign of preeclampsia. Insomnia and difficulty finding comfortable sleeping positions are extremely common. Pelvic pressure and the frequent need to urinate increase as the baby drops lower. Braxton Hicks contractions may become more frequent and more noticeable. Fatigue returns as carrying the extra weight becomes increasingly demanding.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Prenatal Care Checklist</h2>
      <p>Regular prenatal care is one of the most important things you can do for a healthy pregnancy. The standard schedule of prenatal visits in the United States is every four weeks during the first and second trimesters (through week 28), every two weeks from weeks 28 through 36, and weekly from week 36 until delivery.</p>
      <p>Key prenatal appointments and screenings include the first prenatal visit (weeks 6 to 8), which confirms the pregnancy, estimates the due date, and orders baseline lab work. First trimester screening (weeks 11 to 13) includes a blood test and nuchal translucency ultrasound to assess the risk of chromosomal abnormalities. The anatomy scan ultrasound (weeks 18 to 22) provides a detailed examination of the baby's development. The glucose tolerance test (weeks 24 to 28) screens for gestational diabetes. Group B streptococcus screening (weeks 35 to 37) tests for a common bacterium that can be passed to the baby during delivery. Non-stress tests may be ordered in the late third trimester to monitor the baby's heart rate and movement patterns.</p>
      <p>Between visits, contact your healthcare provider if you experience any warning signs, including vaginal bleeding, severe abdominal pain, persistent headache with vision changes, sudden severe swelling, fever above 100.4 degrees Fahrenheit, decreased fetal movement, or fluid leaking from the vagina.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Nutrition During Pregnancy</h2>
      <p>Proper nutrition during pregnancy supports your baby's development, maintains your health, and prepares your body for labor and breastfeeding. Calorie needs increase modestly during pregnancy: no additional calories are needed in the first trimester, approximately 340 extra calories per day in the second trimester, and approximately 450 extra calories per day in the third trimester. The phrase "eating for two" is misleading because the additional calorie needs are relatively small.</p>
      <p>Key nutrients to prioritize include folic acid (600 micrograms daily from supplements and fortified foods to prevent neural tube defects), iron (27 milligrams daily to support the increased blood volume and prevent anemia), calcium (1,000 milligrams daily for the baby's bone development), vitamin D (600 IU daily for calcium absorption and immune function), DHA omega-3 fatty acid (200 to 300 milligrams daily for brain and eye development), and choline (450 milligrams daily for brain development and placental function).</p>
      <p>A prenatal vitamin covers many of these needs but should supplement, not replace, a balanced diet. Focus on lean proteins (chicken, fish, eggs, legumes, tofu), whole grains (oats, brown rice, whole wheat bread), fruits and vegetables (aim for a wide variety of colors to get a range of vitamins and antioxidants), dairy or fortified alternatives (for calcium and vitamin D), and healthy fats (avocados, nuts, olive oil, fatty fish like salmon).</p>
      <p>Stay well hydrated by drinking at least eight to twelve cups of water per day. Adequate hydration supports the increased blood volume, amniotic fluid production, and kidney function required during pregnancy. Dehydration can contribute to headaches, constipation, and in severe cases, preterm contractions. Check our guide on <a href="/blog/how-much-water-should-you-drink/">how much water to drink</a> for general hydration guidelines.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Baby Size Comparisons by Week</h2>
      <p>Tracking your baby's growth is one of the most exciting parts of pregnancy. Here is a week-by-week guide using common fruit and food comparisons to help you visualize your baby's size. At week four, your baby is the size of a poppy seed. By week six, a sweet pea. Week eight, a raspberry. Week ten, a prune. Week twelve, a lime. Week fourteen, a lemon. Week sixteen, an avocado. Week eighteen, a bell pepper. Week twenty, a banana. Week twenty-two, a papaya. Week twenty-four, an ear of corn. Week twenty-six, a head of lettuce. Week twenty-eight, a large eggplant. Week thirty, a head of cabbage. Week thirty-two, a squash. Week thirty-four, a cantaloupe. Week thirty-six, a head of romaine lettuce. Week thirty-eight, a winter melon. Week forty, a small pumpkin, weighing approximately 7 to 8 pounds and measuring about 20 inches long.</p>
      <p>Keep in mind that these are averages and there is significant normal variation in baby size. Your healthcare provider monitors growth through fundal height measurements and ultrasound to ensure your baby is growing at an appropriate rate for its gestational age.</p>
    </section>

